CV responses of the modified electrode towards 5-Fluro uracil, doxycycline, amoxicillin, ciprofloxacin, cloxacillin, histidine, cysteine, glucose, and mandelic acid were performed to examine the selectivity of CD-modified graphitic carbon electrode towards Dox. The selectivity experiment was carried out at pH 6 with a scan rate of 50 mVs−1 (Fig. 9
                         a). To broaden the application of the developed sensor, the detection limit and linear range were determined using differential pulse voltammetry. DPV analysis was carried out by varying the concentration of Dox from 10 to 60 nM. (Fig. 9b). The straight line obtained on plotting Dox concentrations and the peak current indicates the direct relationship between them. The detection limit was calculated as 2.86 nM in the linear range of 10–60 nM. High precision was determined in the case of the modified electrode for Dox determination (Fig. 9c). This incredible detection limit paved the way for precise detection of minute amounts of Dox in aqueous solution as well as future industrial applications. Compared to previous reports, the new sensor detects doxycycline with remarkable selectivity and sensitivity (Table 1
                        ).

Anticancer activity of S.glauca CDs was tested with MCF-7 (Human breast cancer) cells by methyl thiazolyl tetrazolium (MTT) assay. Fig. 12
                      shows the microscopic images of different concentrations of CD (0, 6.5, 12.5, 25, 50, and 100 µL/mL) incubated with MCF-7 cells. The MTT assay revealed that cell viability decreased in a dose-dependent manner (Fig. 13
                     ). The anticancer activity of the S.glauca leaf extract is already reported [57,58]. The LD50 of S.glauca CDs was reported to be 77.02 µL/mL in the current work, indicating that these nanoparticles are effective against the MCF-7 human breast cancer cell line.
